The `multirow` command is part of the `array` and `tabulary` packages and it is used to display a table row that spans multiple rows. The command takes five arguments:

* the first argument specifies the alignment of the contents of the cell
* the second argument is the label for the row
* the third argument is the label for the column
* the fourth and fifth arguments are the contents of the cell

For example, the following code will produce a table with three columns and two rows, where the contents of the second row span across two rows.
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{array}
\begin{document}

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
First & Second & Third \\\hline
Row 1 & Content & Content \\\hline
Row 2 & Content & \multirow{5}{*}{This is the content that spans across two rows} \\\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{document}
```
